12.title: Flu
dlg:
Most of the time, what you think is an ear pain caused by ear infection may actually be referred pain.

The pain may be coming from your teeth, throat, sinuses or TMJ (temporomandibular joint)

0.header:
First, let's see if you need to see a doctor urgently.

If not, we will discuss what is available over-the-counter for earache relief.

1.header: Did you experience a severe sharp ear pain that suddenly stopped?

2.header:
Yes?
Let's make sure you are not looking at a ruptured eardrum.

3.header: Was this sharp pain followed by bloody drainage from the ear canal?

4.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • You may be looking at a ruptured eardrum.

  • Quick treatment is important to preserve your hearing.

  • Complications such as hearing loss can develop.
    Usually, this is temporary and lasts only till the tear or hole in the eardrum has healed. But the size and location of the tear can affect the degree of hearing loss.

  • Risking middle ear infection (otitis media).
    Bacteria can enter your middle ear which might lead to infection that can cause hearing loss later.

  • Complications due to middle ear cyst (cholesteatoma).
    This cyst contains ear wax, dusts, bacteria which the ear drum usually keep out. If your eardrum is ruptured, the debris can pass into your middle ear and form a cyst providing a friendly place for bacteria to grow.

5.header: Was this sharp pain followed by thick pus-filled drainage from the ear canal?

6.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • You may be looking at a ruptured eardrum.
  • Quick treatment is important to preserve your hearing.
  • Complications such as hearing loss can develop.
    Usually, this is temporary and lasts only till the tear or hole in the eardrum has healed. But the size and location of the tear can affect the degree of hearing loss.
  • Risking middle ear infection (otitis media).
    Bacteria can enter your middle ear which might lead to infection that can cause hearing loss later.
  • Complications due to middle ear cyst (cholesteatoma).
    This cyst contains ear wax, dusts, bacteria which the ear drum usually keep out. If your eardrum is ruptured, the debris can pass into your middle ear and form a cyst providing a friendly place for bacteria to grow.

7.header: What about a spinning sensation after this sharp pain?

8.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Propably looking at a ruptured eardrum.
  • Quick treatment is important to preserve your hearing.

9.header: Was it followed by ringing in your ear?

10.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Propably looking at a ruptured eardrum.
  • Quick treatment is important to preserve your hearing.

11.header: Is your face feeling weak after this sharp pain?

12.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Propably looking at a ruptured eardrum.
  • Quick treatment is important to preserve your hearing.

13.header:
Those were signs and symptoms of a ruptured eardrum.

If any applied to you, seek urgent care. You don't want to take chances of hearing loss either now or down the road.

If none apply to you, then let's continue and see what else we may be looking at.

20.header: Any fever or sore throat with this earache?

21.header:
Yes?
Let's make sure you are not looking at an ear infection.

22.header: Do you have fluid draining from the ear with this earache?

23.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • May be looking at an ear infection.

24.header: Do you feel nausea and/or vomiting with this earache?

25.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Possible ear infection.

26.header: What about diarrhea with this earache?

27.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Possible ear infection going on.

28.header: Is there fullness or hearing loss in the affected ear with this earache?

29.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Possible ear infection.

30.header:
Those were possible signs and symptoms of an ear infection in adults.

Seek urgent care if any applied to you. If none apply to your situation, let's continue

40.header: Does the ear canal itch?

41.header: Let's make sure you are not looking at a swimmer's ear infection.

42.header: Any foul smelling, yellow or yellow-green, pus-like discharge from the ear?

44.header:
Hold the ear lobe or outer ear and wiggle it.

Does this earache get worse?

45.header:
Yes?
Possible swimmer's ear infection. Would you like to see our entry on swimmer's ear?

46.header:
Push on the little "bump" in front of your ear.

Does this ear pain you already have get worse?

47.header:
Yes?
Possible swimmer's ear infection. Would you like to see the entry on swimmer's ear?

Symptoms include:

  • Swelling in the ear
  • Itchy ear or ear canal
  • Hurts when you pull on the ear lobe

48.header: Is the inside of the ear red?

49.header:
Yes?
This is a sign of a swimmer's ear infection.

Symptoms of swimmer's ear infection include:

  • Swelling in the ear
  • Itchy ear or ear canal
  • Hurts when you pull on the ear lobe
  • Yellow, yellow-green, pus-like, or foul smelling drainage from the ear.
  • Redness inside the ear

Would you like to see our entry for swimmer's ear or Continue?

50.header:
Those were some of the signs and symptoms of a swimmer's ear infection.

If they apply to you, seek urgent care or call the doctor. You will need antibiotic or steroidal ear drops among other things. None of these are available over-the-counter.

If none apply to you or you don't think this is swimmer's ear infection, let's continue and figure this earache out.

60.header: With this ear pain, are you having difficulty chewing or biting?

61.header: Let's make sure you are not looking at temporomandibular joint (TMJ) disorder.

62.header:
Try opening or closing the mouth.

Does the jaw joint "crack" when doing this?

63.header:
Yes?
Hope we are not looking at TMJ.
Let's Continue.

64.header:
Alright
What about jaw pain or tenderness of the jaw...

...With this ear pain?

65.header:
Yes?
Hmmm, hope you are not looking at TMJ

Symptoms of TMJ include:

  • Difficulty chewing or biting stuff
  • Jaw joint "crack" when opening or closing the mouth
  • Jaw pain or tenderness of the jaw.

66.header: Does your jaw lock?

67.header:
It locks?
We are thinking TMJ.

Symptoms of TMJ include:

  • Difficulty chewing or biting stuff
  • Jaw joint "crack" when opening or closing the mouth
  • Jaw pain or tenderness of the jaw
  • Locking of the jaw.

68.header: Alright. Are you experiencing a dull, aching pain in the face?

69.header:
Yes?
This can be a symptom of TMJ disorder.

Symptoms of TMJ include:

  • Difficulty chewing or biting stuff
  • Jaw joint "crack" when opening or closing the mouth
  • Jaw pain or tenderness of the jaw
  • Locking of the jaw
  • Dull, aching pain in the face.

If you are looking at these symptoms, you will have to see a doctor as soon as possible.

70.header:
Well.
Those were the signs and symptoms of a TMJ disorder.

If you think you are looking at one, see a dentist or call your doctor for complete evaluation.

If not, let's continue and see what else might be causing this earache you are experiencing before we see what a pharmacist recommend you use over-the-counter.

80.header: Are you experiencing a sensation that the ear is plugged with this earache?

81.header:
Yes?
Let's rule out earwax blockade.

82.header: Are you hearing noises in the affected ear?

84.header: Does the ear feel full to you with a partial hearing loss?

85.header:
Yes?
This is a symptom of earwax blocking the ear canal.

If a feeling of fullness in the ear or partial hearing loss is what you are experiencing with this ear pain, we may probably be looking at earwax blocking the ear canal. Check out the entry for earwax for a more detailed discussion.

If this is not the case, let's continue.

86.header:
Alright
We just went through some of the signs of earwax blocking the ear canal.

If a feeling of fullness in the ear or partial hearing loss is what you are experiencing with this ear pain, we may probably be looking at earwax blocking the ear canal. Check out the entry for earwax for a more detailed discussion.

If this is not the case, let's continue.

90.header:
Try biting down on the same side as the ear pain.

Do you feel a toothache?

91.header:
Yes?
You may have a toothache pain that is radiating to the ear on the same side.

Would you like to see our entry for tootache or Continue if you don't think so?

92.header: Are you hearing fluid in the ear that yawning or coughing cannot get rid of with this earache?

94.header: What about feeling pressure in the ear that yawning or coughing does not get rid of?

95.header:
Yes?
More than likely looking at a sinus pressure situation causing the earache.

Pressure in the sinus cavities from a cold or sinus infection can increase the pressure in the middle ear causing it to ache.

96.header:
Alright
We tried to look at causes of earache.

Other causes of earache that you may come accross include earache during or after a flight (Barotruama).

For what may be causing your earache that we did not touch, seek urgent care if the pain is serious or call the primary care doctor.

Let's see what a pharmacist recommend until you can do that.

100.header: How bad is this earache on a scale of 1 to 10?

101.header:
You said:{{currentTemp}}

 

1 to 3

Send to pharmacist

102.header:
You said:{{currentTemp}}

 

4 to 7

Advice and send to pharmacist

103.header:
You said:{{currentTemp}}

 

Seek urgent care.

13.title: Swimmer's Ear
dlg:
Persistent moisture in the ear canal from let's say frequent swimming can lead to loss of earwax and ultimately a breakdown of the defense system against ear infection.

Bacteria grow in the presence of this moist conditions and infect the ear.

0.header:
Swimmer's ear is an infection of the outer ear canal.

Let's see how you can go about taking care of this.

1.header:
Let's find out if this is swimmer's ear infection.

Then we will see how bad it is and figure out what to do from there.

2.header:
Hold the ear lobe or outer ear and wiggle it.

Do you feel any pain or does the pain you already have get worse?

4.header:
Push on the little "bump" in front of your ear.

Is there any pain or does the pain you already have get worse?

5.header:
No?
You may want to see a doctor if you think you have swimmer's ear.

Swimmer's ear is infection of the external ear and pushing on this area should give you some kind of discomfort.

6.header: Are you experiencing itching in your ear canal?

7.header:
No?
Hmmm. Swimmer's ear symptoms usually include itching in the ear canal.

8.header: What about feeling of fullness inside the ear?

9.header:
No such feeling?
Usually with swimmer's ear, accumulated debris in the ear gives you a feeling of fullness in the ear.

This is especially so when they trap water inside hence the name swimmer's ear.
If you think it is swimmer's ear, then let's Continue.

10.header:
If answer is yes so far, suspect swimmer's ear infection.

If you are thinking swimmer's ear, most of the time you will have to see a doctor. You will need some kind of antibiotic, steroidal or acetic acid ear drops and even removal of the debris in the ear.

Let's see how bad it is and determine the best course of action to take.

20.header: Is there a foul-smelling discharge coming from the ear?

21.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Looking at an infection.
  • No over-the-counter stuff would take care of this.
  • What over-the-counter drops do is attempt to dry the water in the ear. They don't take care of any infection or inflammation going on in the ear.
  • Moreover, with discharge coming from the ear canal, it might be due to a ruptured eardrum or something more serious. So you must see a doctor.

22.header: Does the ear appear red or swollen?

23.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Looking at an infection.
  • Over the counter medications won't take care of any infection or inflammation going on in the ear.

24.header: Do you have fever with this ear pain?

25.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • May be looking at an infection.

26.header:
What about severe pain that goes to your face or neck?

Or side of the head?

27.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Looking at serious inflammation and infection

28.header: Are you experiencing swelling in the lymph nodes in your neck?

29.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Possibility of a serious infection
  • Serious inflammation.

30.header: Is your ear canal completely blocked?

31.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Will need to have debris removed
  • Risk of ear infection is high

32.header:
Doctors classify swimmer's ear infection into mild,  moderate and advanced.

If you answered No to the questions so far, then you do not have the advanced stage of progression. At least not yet.

Let's see if we are looking at the moderate stage of swimmer's ear infection.

40.header:
Are you experiencing a pus-like drainage that is foul smelling?

Could be yellow to yellow green.

41.header: This is a symptom of a moderate stage of swimmer's ear infection.

42.header: What about partial blockage of your ear canal by swelling or fluid?

43.header:
Yes?
This is a sign of a moderate stage of swimmer's ear infection.

44.header: Is the itching getting more intense?

46.header: What about increasing ear pain?

48.header: Is your hearing muffled and reduced?

50.header:
Alright.
Those were the signs and symptoms of a moderate stage.

The moderate case of a swimmer's ear infection require professional care. You should seek urgent care or call the doctor if you think you are looking at one.

We are talking about an infection here, and it will become worse the more you delay treatment. You need to get started on some antibiotics, steroidal ear drop or something to dry out the fluid.

Would you like to see the nearest urgent care clinic to you or Continue?

60.header:
Great.
Let's take a look at a mild case of swimmer's ear infection.

62.header: Are you seeing drainage of clear, odorless fluid

63.header:
Yes?
This is a sign of a mild case of swimmer's ear infection.

When you start seeing yellow to yellowish green pus, then you will be looking at a moderate case.

64.header: Are you experiencing a mild pain made worse by pulling on the ear?

65.header:
Yes?
If the pain is not intense, then you are probably looking at a mild case.

66.header:
Is the ear canal slightly red?

And itchy?

67.header:
Yes?
Probably looking at a mild case of swimmer's ear infection.

68.header:
Those were signs and symptoms of a mild case of swimmer's ear infection.

If you think it is a swimmer's ear infection, if mild or not, we strongly recommend you see the doctor as soon as possible to avoid further damage to the ear.

The keyword here is infection. So you will need an antibiotic ear drop.

Would you like to visit the nearest urgent care clinic or see what a pharmacist recommend you do for swimmer's ear until you can see a doctor?

14.title: Ear Wax
dlg:
Wax is a sticky liquid (not really wax) called cerumen that helps protect the ear canal by suppressing bacteria growth in the canal, trapping dirt and other small particles and even insects.

It should wash away along with the trapped debris naturally by jaw movements drying and falling out from the ear without you even knowing, but then again with wax, the build up may get hard and keep getting larger.

0.header:
Let's see what is available for earwax removal over-the-counter.

How do you know you have ear wax problem anyway? Let's find out first.

1.header: Which of these are you experiencing at the moment?

options.title: Feeling of fullness in the ear
Decreased hearing in the affected ear
Sensation that the ear is plugged

1.except: Oops!, You told me nothing

2.header:
None of these?
You may not have ear wax blockage then.

Would you like to continue and see our discussion regarding ear wax or check out something else?

3.header:
All of the above?
Well let's rule out other things that may cause these.

4.header:
Also earache?
Ear wax can cause this, let's rule out other causes of earache.

5.header:
Alright
These can be a sign and symptom of ear wax.

Let's continue and rule out other causes of these signs and symptoms.

10.header: Are you experiencing hearing loss or reduced hearing in one or both ears?

12.header: Did you recently have an ear infection?

14.header: Are you experiencing any fever?

15.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • You might be looking at an ear infection
  • Fever is a sign you body is fighting something.

16.header: What about drainage of fluid from the ear?

17.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • You might be looking at an ear infection.

18.header: Have you had ear wax problems in the past?

19.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Further evaluation required to be sure it is related to ear wax blockage.
